estershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"about 1370–12 April 1454":"about 1370–12 April 1454","1370–1454":"1370–1454","1375–1448":"1375–1448","1372–1440":"1372–1440","1393–1460":"1393–1460","1396–Female":"1396–Deceased","1340–1393":"1340–1393","about 1370":"about 1370","about 1393":"about 1393","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1460":"1460","1372":"1372","1393":"1393","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","after 1434":"after 1434","1448":"1448","1454":"1454","12 April 1454":"12 April 1454","1375":"1375","about 1440":"about 1440","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Mildenhall, Wiltshire, England":"Mildenhall, Wiltshire, England","Poulton, Wiltshire, England":"Poulton, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Goddard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from <i>Godhard</i>, a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i>, <i>got</i> ‘god’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The name was popular in Europe during the Middle Ages as a result of the fame of Saint Gotthard, an 11th-century bishop of Hildesheim who founded a hospice on the pass from Switzerland to Italy that bears his name. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","English: perhaps occasionally a variant of the occupational name   Gothard  . The two surnames may have been much confused.","French: variant of   Godard  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Gothard","meanings":["English: variant of   Goddard  .","English: occupational name for a keeper of goats, from Middle English <i>gotherde</i> (Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>hierde</i>) ‘herdsman, keeper’.","English: variant of <b>Goater</b>, with excrescent <i>-d</i>, either a topographic name for someone who lived by a stream or ditch, from Middle English <i>gote</i> ‘watercourse’ + the agent suffix <i>-(e)r</i>, or an occupational name either from Middle English <i>gotherde</i> ‘goatherd’ or from Middle English <i>goter</i> ‘goatherd’, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>got(e)</i> ‘goat’ (Old English <i>gāt</i>)."]},{"name":"Godard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Reynald, Alcide, Armand, Aurel, Celine, Cyprien, Dominique, Emile, Etienne, Euclide, Gilles.","French: from the personal name <i>Godard</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Goddard  ).","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Goddard  , a cognate of 1 above. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Goertz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Christoph, Erwin, Guenter, Juergen, Kurt, Otto.","German (also <b>Görtz</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Goert</i>, a short form of <i>Godhard</i> (see   Goddard  ),   Gottfried   or   Gerhardt  , common in Rhineland.","Germanized form (also <b>Görtz</b>) of Sorbian <b>Gerc</b>; see   Gertz  ."]},{"name":"Goodart","meanings":["English: variant of   Goddard  .","Perhaps also an Americanized form of German   Gothard  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Goddard of Poulton was born about 1370, in Gloucestershire, England as the son of John Goddard. He married Cecily Mildenhall in 1392, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 12 April 1454, in Mildenhall, Wiltshire, England, at the age of 85, and was buried in Mildenhall, Wiltshire, England."},"et":{"about 1370–12 April 1454":"umbes 1370–12. aprill 1454","1370–1454":"1370–1454","1375–1448":"1375–1448","1372–1440":"1372–1440","1393–1460":"1393–1460","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1340–1393":"1340–1393","about 1370":"umbes 1370","about 1393":"umbes 1393","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1460":"1460","1372":"1372","1393":"1393","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","after 1434":"pärast 1434","1448":"1448","1454":"1454","12 April 1454":"12. aprill 1454","1375":"1375","about 1440":"umbes 1440","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mildenhall, Wiltshire, England":"Mildenhall, Wiltshire, England","Poulton, Wiltshire, England":"Poulton, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1370–12 April 1454":"noin 1370–12. huhtikuuta 1454","1370–1454":"1370–1454","1375–1448":"1375–1448","1372–1440":"1372–1440","1393–1460":"1393–1460","1396–Female":"1396–Kuollut","1340–1393":"1340–1393","about 1370":"noin 1370","about 1393":"noin 1393","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1460":"1460","1372":"1372","1393":"1393","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","after 1434":"1434 jälkeen","1448":"1448","1454":"1454","12 April 1454":"12. huhtikuuta 1454","1375":"1375","about 1440":"noin 1440","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Mildenhall, Wiltshire, England":"Mild